      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the belief that the Constitution should be interpreted based on the original understanding \"at the time it was adopted.\" The main legal justifications for originalism are that it preserves the intent of the Founding Fathers, prevents judges from imposing their personal values, and maintains the stability and predictability of the law. Originalists argue that the Constitution is a legal document that should be applied as it was written, not as it might be interpreted today. This approach respects the democratic process by deferring to the original meaning of the text, which was determined by the people and their elected representatives at the time of ratification. Originalism also limits judicial activism, ensuring that judges do not overstep their boundaries and make law rather than interpret it.",
